{
  "Hormones are:": "",
  "Enzymes that digest food": "",
  "Structural proteins in bone": "",
  "Nerve impulses": "",
  "Chemical messengers secreted into the bloodstream": "",
  "Hormones are chemical messengers produced by endocrine glands and transported through the bloodstream to act on distant target cells.": "",
  "Endocrine glands are called 'ductless' because they:": "",
  "Are not considered real glands": "",
  "Secrete into body cavities": "",
  "Have no products to secrete": "",
  "Secrete hormones directly into the blood without using ducts": "",
  "Unlike exocrine glands that use ducts to deliver secretions to surfaces, endocrine glands release hormones directly into the surrounding capillaries for distribution through the bloodstream.": "",
  "Steroid hormones are derived from:": "",
  "Glucose": "",
  "Cholesterol": "",
  "Amino acids": "",
  "ATP": "",
  "Steroid hormones such as cortisol, estrogen, and testosterone are synthesized from cholesterol through a series of enzymatic conversions that modify the four-ring steroid backbone.": "",
  "Insulin is classified as a _____ hormone.": "",
  "Peptide (protein)": "",
  "Lipid": "",
  "Steroid": "",
  "Eicosanoid": "",
  "Insulin is a peptide hormone composed of 51 amino acids arranged in two polypeptide chains linked by disulfide bonds, produced by beta cells in the pancreatic islets.": "",
  "Water-soluble hormones such as peptides signal target cells by:": "",
  "Crossing the cell membrane directly to enter the nucleus": "",
  "Dissolving into the lipid bilayer permanently": "",
  "Converting into steroid hormones first": "",
  "Binding to cell surface receptors and activating second messengers": "",
  "Because water-soluble hormones cannot cross the hydrophobic lipid bilayer, they must bind receptors on the cell surface and relay their signal through intracellular second messengers like cAMP.": "",
  "cAMP is an example of a:": "",
  "Hormone": "",
  "Steroid precursor": "",
  "Receptor protein": "",
  "Second messenger": "",
  "Cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) is one of the most common second messengers, relaying and amplifying the hormone's signal inside the cell after the hormone binds its surface receptor.": "",
  "The hypothalamus connects the nervous and endocrine systems by:": "",
  "Being a bone structure that protects the brain": "",
  "Producing releasing and inhibiting hormones that control the pituitary gland": "",
  "Only processing sensory information from the eyes": "",
  "Acting solely as a muscle controller": "",
  "The hypothalamus serves as the primary neuroendocrine link, receiving neural input and translating it into hormonal signals that regulate the anterior and posterior pituitary gland.": "",
  "Hormone specificity depends on:": "",
  "The size of the endocrine gland producing the hormone": "",
  "Hormone concentration alone": "",
  "The blood type of the individual": "",
  "The presence of specific receptors on target cells": "",
  "A hormone can only affect a cell that has the matching receptor for it; without the correct receptor, the cell cannot respond to the hormone regardless of its concentration in the blood.": "",
  "The endocrine system works _____ compared to the nervous system.": "",
  "Faster with shorter-lasting effects": "",
  "At the same speed with identical effects": "",
  "More slowly but with longer-lasting effects": "",
  "Without any measurable effect on the body": "",
  "Hormonal responses typically take seconds to hours to begin but can last for days, whereas neural signals travel in milliseconds but are brief, making the two systems complementary.": "",
  "Hormone levels are regulated primarily by:": "",
  "Negative feedback loops": "",
  "Voluntary conscious control": "",
  "Positive feedback exclusively": "",
  "Random secretion with no control": "",
  "Negative feedback is the dominant regulatory mechanism for most hormones, in which rising hormone levels inhibit further release to maintain homeostasis around a set point.": "",
  "What is an endocrine gland?": "",
  "A ductless gland that secretes hormones directly into the bloodstream": "",
  "A gland that secretes products through ducts onto body surfaces": "",
  "Any organ that produces enzymes for digestion": "",
  "A gland found only in the reproductive system": "",
  "An endocrine gland is a ductless organ that synthesizes hormones and releases them directly into the blood, in contrast to exocrine glands which use ducts to deliver secretions to epithelial surfaces.": "",
  "What does the term 'second messenger' mean in hormone signaling?": "",
  "A protein that transports hormones in the blood": "",
  "A backup receptor that activates if the primary receptor fails": "",
  "A second hormone released after the first one": "",
  "An intracellular molecule that relays and amplifies the signal from a hormone bound to a surface receptor": "",
  "A second messenger is an intracellular signaling molecule, such as cAMP or IP3, that is generated after a hormone (the first messenger) binds its cell-surface receptor, amplifying and transmitting the signal within the cell.": "",
  "What is up-regulation?": "",
  "The destruction of receptors by enzymes": "",
  "A decrease in the number of receptors on a target cell": "",
  "The movement of a gland to a higher position in the body": "",
  "An increase in the number of receptors on a target cell, increasing its sensitivity to a hormone": "",
  "Up-regulation occurs when a cell increases the number of receptors for a particular hormone, typically in response to prolonged low hormone levels, making the cell more sensitive to even small amounts of that hormone.": "",
  "What does 'down-regulation' mean?": "",
  "The process of a gland shrinking in size": "",
  "The suppression of nerve impulses to an endocrine gland": "",
  "An increase in hormone production by a gland": "",
  "A decrease in the number of hormone receptors on a target cell, reducing sensitivity": "",
  "Down-regulation is the process by which prolonged exposure to high hormone levels causes target cells to reduce the number of their receptors, thereby decreasing their responsiveness to that hormone.": "",
  "What is a paracrine signal?": "",
  "A chemical signal that acts on nearby cells without entering the bloodstream": "",
  "A hormone that travels through the bloodstream to distant targets": "",
  "A neural signal transmitted along an axon": "",
  "A signal that only affects the cell that produced it": "",
  "Paracrine signals are chemical messengers like prostaglandins and histamine that act locally on neighboring cells, diffusing through the interstitial fluid rather than traveling through the bloodstream.": "",
  "What does 'half-life' mean when referring to a hormone?": "",
  "Half the time between hormone release and receptor binding": "",
  "The point at which a hormone reaches half of its maximum potency": "",
  "The time it takes for a gland to produce half of its hormone supply": "",
  "The time required for half the circulating hormone to be broken down or removed from the blood": "",
  "A hormone's half-life is the time needed for its blood concentration to decrease by half, which determines how long the hormone's effects persist and how frequently it must be secreted to maintain adequate levels.": "",
  "What is an autocrine signal?": "",
  "An electrical signal between neurons": "",
  "A hormone that circulates in the bloodstream": "",
  "A chemical signal that acts on the same cell that produced it": "",
  "A signal from one endocrine gland to another": "",
  "An autocrine signal is a chemical messenger released by a cell that binds to receptors on that same cell, allowing the cell to regulate its own activity, as seen with certain growth factors and immune cell cytokines.": "",
  "What are catecholamines?": "",
  "Peptide hormones produced by the thyroid gland": "",
  "Amino acid-derived hormones including epinephrine, norepinephrine, and dopamine, synthesized from tyrosine": "",
  "Lipid-based signaling molecules found in the kidneys": "",
  "Steroid hormones produced by the adrenal cortex": "",
  "Catecholamines are a class of amino acid-derived hormones and neurotransmitters synthesized from the amino acid tyrosine, including dopamine, norepinephrine, and epinephrine, primarily produced by the adrenal medulla and sympathetic neurons.": "",
  "What does 'negative feedback' mean in the context of hormone regulation?": "",
  "A regulatory mechanism in which rising hormone levels inhibit further hormone release, maintaining homeostasis": "",
  "A feedback loop that only occurs in the nervous system": "",
  "The body produces increasingly more hormone without any limit": "",
  "The complete shutdown of a gland after a single burst of hormone release": "",
  "Negative feedback is the most common regulatory mechanism for hormones, in which the product of a pathway (the hormone) inhibits earlier steps in that pathway, preventing overproduction and keeping levels within a normal physiological range.": "",
  "What is a prostaglandin?": "",
  "A protein receptor found on target cells": "",
  "A peptide hormone that regulates blood sugar": "",
  "A steroid hormone derived from cholesterol": "",
  "A lipid-derived local chemical mediator involved in inflammation, pain, and other local responses": "",
  "Prostaglandins are eicosanoids derived from arachidonic acid (a fatty acid) that act as local paracrine signals involved in inflammation, pain sensation, blood clotting, and regulation of smooth muscle contraction.": "",
  "A researcher notices that when she adds a specific hormone to a cell culture, no intracellular response occurs even though the hormone is present in high concentrations. When she examines the cells, she finds they lack the receptor for that hormone. Which principle of endocrine signaling does this best demonstrate?": "",
  "Hormones must be in extremely high concentrations to work": "",
  "Second messengers are not required for any hormone signaling": "",
  "The hormone must be a steroid to enter the cell": "",
  "Hormone specificity depends on the presence of matching receptors on target cells": "",
  "This scenario illustrates the lock-and-key principle of hormone specificity: a hormone can only exert its effect on cells that express the appropriate receptor, and without that receptor the cell cannot respond regardless of hormone concentration.": "",
  "A medical student is studying a patient who has chronically elevated levels of a particular hormone. Lab results show the target cells now have fewer receptors for that hormone. What phenomenon is this patient experiencing?": "",
  "Autocrine signaling failure": "",
  "Down-regulation of receptors": "",
  "Positive feedback amplification": "",
  "Up-regulation of receptors": "",
  "Chronic exposure to high hormone levels triggers down-regulation, where target cells decrease their receptor numbers as a protective mechanism, reducing sensitivity and preventing excessive stimulation.": "",
  "A pharmacology student is learning about a new drug that mimics a peptide hormone. Her professor explains that the drug cannot cross the cell membrane. How would this drug most likely signal the target cell?": "",
  "By binding to an intracellular receptor in the cytoplasm": "",
  "By binding to a cell-surface receptor and activating intracellular second messengers like cAMP": "",
  "By diffusing through the membrane and binding to nuclear receptors": "",
  "By directly altering DNA transcription without any receptor": "",
  "Like peptide hormones, water-soluble drugs that cannot cross the lipid bilayer must bind cell-surface receptors and rely on second messenger cascades (such as cAMP or IP3) to transmit the signal intracellularly.": "",
  "A patient is prescribed a synthetic steroid medication. The physician explains that the drug works by entering cells and changing gene expression. Which mechanism of hormone action does this represent?": "",
  "Crossing the cell membrane and binding to intracellular or nuclear receptors that act as transcription factors": "",
  "Being converted to a peptide hormone before acting": "",
  "Binding to cell-surface receptors and activating cAMP": "",
  "Activating paracrine signaling in nearby cells only": "",
  "Steroid hormones are lipid-soluble and can pass directly through the cell membrane to bind intracellular or nuclear receptors, forming a hormone-receptor complex that acts as a transcription factor to alter gene expression.": "",
  "During a physiology lab, a student observes that adding a tiny amount of epinephrine to a tissue sample produces a dramatic cellular response. The professor notes that the signal was amplified thousands of times within the cell. Which component of the signaling pathway is most responsible for this amplification?": "",
  "The gland releasing more hormone in response to the tissue": "",
  "The second messenger cascade, where each step activates many downstream molecules": "",
  "The hormone itself multiplying in the bloodstream": "",
  "The receptor doubling in size after hormone binding": "",
  "The second messenger cascade provides signal amplification because each activated enzyme in the pathway activates many copies of the next enzyme, allowing a single hormone-receptor event to generate thousands of intracellular responses.": "",
  "A nurse notices that a patient with severe chronic illness has become less responsive to a hormone therapy that initially worked well. Blood levels of the hormone are actually higher than normal. What is the most likely explanation for the decreased response?": "",
  "The target cells have undergone down-regulation, reducing receptor numbers despite high hormone levels": "",
  "The hormone has changed its molecular structure": "",
  "The patient has developed new endocrine glands": "",
  "The patient's liver is producing extra hormone": "",
  "Prolonged exposure to elevated hormone levels commonly leads to down-regulation, where target cells internalize and degrade receptors, reducing their total number and making the cells less responsive despite adequate or excessive hormone concentrations.": "",
  "A student is comparing the response times of the nervous and endocrine systems for an exam. She notes that when a person touches a hot stove, the hand withdraws in milliseconds, but when blood glucose rises, insulin takes minutes to noticeably lower it. What fundamental difference explains this?": "",
  "The endocrine system only functions during sleep when the brain enters a parasympathetic state, and all hormone secretion ceases entirely during waking hours": "",
  "Neural signals are electrochemical and travel rapidly along neurons, while hormones must be secreted into and transported through the bloodstream, producing slower but longer-lasting effects": "",
  "Insulin is a steroid hormone derived from cholesterol, and all steroid hormones act slowly because they must diffuse through the cell membrane and bind intracellular receptors": "",
  "The nervous system uses specialized neurosecretory hormones that are structurally different from endocrine hormones and travel through dedicated neural channels much faster than blood": "",
  "The nervous system transmits electrochemical impulses along dedicated neural pathways at high speed for rapid responses, while the endocrine system relies on hormones traveling through the bloodstream, resulting in slower onset but more sustained, widespread effects.": "",
  "A physician is treating a patient with an inflammatory condition using anti-prostaglandin medication (such as ibuprofen). The patient asks why the drug reduces pain and swelling. Which explanation is most accurate?": "",
  "The drug increases cAMP production in nerve cells": "",
  "The drug blocks steroid hormone production in the adrenal glands": "",
  "The drug inhibits the synthesis of prostaglandins, which are local lipid mediators that promote inflammation and pain signaling": "",
  "The drug destroys the endocrine glands that cause inflammation": "",
  "Prostaglandins are paracrine lipid mediators synthesized from arachidonic acid that promote inflammation, pain, and fever; drugs like ibuprofen work by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, thereby reducing prostaglandin production and alleviating symptoms.": "",
  "During a lecture on childbirth, a student learns that uterine contractions cause the release of oxytocin, which in turn causes stronger contractions and even more oxytocin release. This continues until the baby is delivered. What type of feedback loop is this?": "",
  "No feedback, because oxytocin acts independently": "",
  "Paracrine signaling, because oxytocin only affects nearby cells": "",
  "Negative feedback, because the process eventually stops": "",
  "Positive feedback, because the response amplifies the original stimulus until a specific endpoint is reached": "",
  "This is a classic example of positive feedback, where the product (oxytocin-induced contractions) amplifies the stimulus (pressure on the cervix), creating an escalating cycle that continues until the event (delivery) is complete and the stimulus is removed.": "",
  "A patient with a thyroid condition is prescribed a hormone that is lipid-soluble. The patient asks why the medication must be taken consistently for weeks before full effects are noticed, unlike a fast-acting pain reliever. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "All medications take weeks to work regardless of their mechanism": "",
  "Lipid-soluble hormones alter gene expression and protein synthesis, which takes longer to produce physiological changes compared to fast-acting second messenger pathways": "",
  "Lipid-soluble hormones are destroyed immediately and must be rebuilt each day": "",
  "The patient's receptors need to be surgically activated first": "",
  "Lipid-soluble hormones like thyroid hormones enter cells and modify gene transcription, leading to new protein synthesis; this genomic mechanism produces longer-lasting but slower-onset effects compared to the rapid second messenger cascades used by water-soluble hormones.": ""
}